9. Customer Acquisition Cost by Channel
Different marketing channels generate customers at different costs. Some channels may appear effective based on volume but perform poorly on cost efficiency. Tracking CPA across channels—content syndication, email marketing, account-based marketing, install base targeting—reveals which investments deliver the best returns.

This metric guides budget reallocation toward high-performing channels while optimizing or eliminating underperforming initiatives. In 2026, data shows that integrated, omnichannel approaches consistently outperform single-channel strategies.

10. Return on Marketing Investment (ROMI)
ROMI measures the revenue generated for every dollar spent on marketing. Calculating ROMI requires proper attribution modeling and clear understanding of which activities drive revenue. Organizations achieving ROMI ratios above 5:1 typically maintain competitive advantage and funding for scaling initiatives.

Progressive companies now track ROMI by segment, campaign, and channel to identify which investments generate the strongest returns. This granular analysis informs strategic decisions about resource allocation and campaign optimization.

11. Sales Cycle Length
How long does it take from initial contact to closed deal? Sales cycle length varies significantly by industry and deal size, but tracking trends over time reveals whether your demand generation and sales enablement efforts are working effectively.

Improving sales cycle length by even a few days can have substantial impact on annual revenue. Strategies like content syndication, targeted email sequences, and account-based marketing are specifically designed to accelerate buying timelines by addressing prospect concerns earlier in their journey.

12. Win Rate and Deal Size
What percentage of qualified opportunities convert to customers, and what is the average contract value? These metrics combined reveal the efficiency of your sales process and the quality of leads marketing provides.

Organizations focused on account-based marketing typically see higher win rates and larger deal sizes than those using traditional lead generation. This reflects the targeting precision and account fit inherent in ABM methodologies.

13. Brand Awareness and Consideration Metrics
Quantifying brand awareness may seem difficult, but it's measurable through search volume for branded terms, share of voice in your industry, and brand lift studies. Consideration metrics track how often your company appears in prospect research and competitive evaluations.

In 2026, sophisticated B2B organizations use intent data and research signals to understand when prospects are actively considering solutions. This intelligence enables precise timing of outreach and messaging.

14. Content Engagement and Performance
Which content assets generate the most qualified engagement? Tracking downloads, time-on-page, and subsequent actions reveals which educational resources resonate most strongly with your target audience.

High-performing B2B organizations recognize content as a demand generation engine. Strategic content syndication, email sequences, and account-based messaging work together to engage prospects and accelerate their buying journey.

15. Customer Retention and Expansion Revenue
Your marketing impact extends beyond acquisition. How effectively does your organization retain customers and expand revenue within existing accounts? Retention metrics and expansion revenue directly impact CLV and overall profitability.

Organizations that implement strategic account-based marketing principles post-sale see significantly higher retention and expansion rates. This integrated approach treats customer success as an extension of demand generation.

